      What is Python used for?
      Python is a general-purpose coding language—which means that, unlike HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, it can be used for other types of programming and software development besides web development. That includes back end development, software development, data science and writing system scripts among other things.

      What is Python exactly?
      Python is an interpreted, object-oriented, high-level programming language with dynamic semantics. ... Python's simple, easy to learn syntax emphasizes readability and therefore reduces the cost of program maintenance. Python supports modules and packages, which encourages program modularity and code reuse.

      Python snake
      Pythons
      Snake
      Python is a genus of constricting snakes in the Pythonidae family native to the tropics and subtropics of the Eastern Hemisphere. The name Python was proposed by François Marie Daudin in 1803 for non-venomous flecked snakes. Currently, 10 python species are recognized as valid taxa.

      Python

      High-level programming language

      Description

      Description

      Python is an interpreted, high-level and general-purpose programming language. Python's design philosophy emphasizes code readability with its notable use of significant indentation. Wikipedia
      Preview release: 3.10.0a6 / 1 March 2021; 33 days ago
      Typing discipline: Duck, dynamic, strong typing; gradual (since 3.5, but ignored in CPython)
      First appeared: February 1991; 30 years ago
      Designed by: Guido van Rossum
      Paradigm: Multi-paradigm: object-oriented, procedural (imperative), functional, structured, reflective
      OS: Linux, macOS, Windows 8 and later; and more
      Range
      Python range() Function

      The range() function returns a sequence of numbers, starting from 0 by default, and increments by 1 (by default), and stops before a specified number.
